{"id": 80, "ts": 1778799288.3041525, "event": "public_discussion_message", "round": 3, "agent": "agent_2", "message": "I\u2019ve now gathered the full set of attributes for each candidate:\n- **Candidate\u202fA** \u2013 Strong situational awareness (anticipates danger, sees complex connections, excellent spatial vision) and very good leadership qualities, but is described as a show\u2011off, not open to new ideas, unorganized and resistant to criticism. No data on stress handling or crew\u2011feedback.\n- **Candidate\u202fB** \u2013 Very conscientious, handles stress well, assesses weather accurately and has excellent computer skills \u2013 all core technical and cognitive needs for long\u2011haul flights. Weaknesses are a weak numeric memory and consistent crew\u2011feedback that he is grumpy and uncooperative. No leadership information or positive crew feedback.\n- **Candidate\u202fC** \u2013 100\u202f% reliable, makes quick correct decisions, keeps calm in a crisis, understands complicated technology and is praised for \u201ccreating a positive atmosphere with his crew,\u201d \u201cputting concern for others above everything,\u201d and being fully reliable. Weaknesses are difficulty communicating ideas, an egocentric reputation and a lack of willingness to pursue further education. No explicit leadership data, but the crew\u2011feedback is wholly positive.\n- **Candidate\u202fD** \u2013 Responds adequately to unexpected events, concentrates very well, solves problems extremely well and takes responsibility seriously. However, he is regarded as arrogant, has a hot temper, weak leadership, and is described as a loner. No data on calmness under pressure or crew\u2011cooperation.\n**Weighing the selection criteria**\n1. **Reliability & decision\u2011making** \u2013 A, B, C and D all have solid points, but C is explicitly 100\u202f% reliable and known for quick, correct decisions.\n2. **Technical & cognitive competence** \u2013 B leads on weather assessment and computer skills; A has excellent spatial vision; D excels at problem\u2011solving; C shows solid technical understanding through his decision\u2011making and calmness.\n3. **Calmness under pressure** \u2013 B handles stress well; C keeps calm in a crisis; A and D have no evidence.\n4. **Teamwork & communication** \u2013 C is the only candidate with documented positive crew atmosphere and concern for others, despite some communication difficulty. B\u2019s crew feedback is negative (grumpy, uncooperative); A is unfriendly and resistant to criticism; D is arrogant and a loner.\n5. **Professional development** \u2013 B and A show no issues; C\u2019s reluctance to further education could affect long\u2011term growth but does not impact immediate safety; D\u2019s attitude issues also limit development.\nGiven the critical importance of sustained crew cohesion, calm decision\u2011making, and reliability on long\u2011distance flights, **Candidate\u202fC** offers the most balanced package. His proven calmness, rapid correct decisions, and positive crew dynamics outweigh the communication and development concerns, which are less likely to jeopardize safety on current operations.\nIf anyone has any additional leadership information for Candidate\u202fC or any positive crew feedback for Candidate\u202fB that could shift this balance, please share.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate C\"}"}
